ce:section.ce:para:
To some extent, the electron transfer efficiency determines the conductivity of the electrode in electrocatalytic systems. Electrochemical impedance tests were performed to evaluate the conductivity of various electrodes, and the results are presented in Fig. 3
                        (a). Additionally, the Nyquist plots were fitted with ZSimWin software, and the fitted resistance Rct reacted to the charge transfer resistance between the solution and the electrode surface (Table 1
                        ). Ti electrode, BCQD/Ti electrode, and Pd-BCQD/Ti electrode were found to have charge transfer resistances (Rct) of 3643, 1768, and 1219 Ω cm2, respectively. When compared to other materials, the Pd-BCQD/Ti electrode has the lowest Rct value, indicating that it has good conductive ability and may go through electron transfer processes with lower resistance and higher electrocatalytic efficiency. Compared to the Rct of the Ti electrode (3643 Ω cm2) and the BCQD/Ti electrode (1768 Ω cm2), it is much lower. The findings demonstrate that Pd and BCQD addition can greatly enhance electron conduction efficiency. Fig. 3(b) shows the polarization curves of the three electrodes. Under the same circumstances, the electrocatalytic performance and hydrogen evolution activity increase with the electrodes' positive hydrogen evolution. The Pd-BCQD/Ti composite electrode has a comparatively larger positive shift than the BCQD/Ti electrode at the same current density, as shown in Fig. 3(b). Compared to the Ti electrodes, the positive hydrogen evolution of both electrodes are higher. According to the data, the Pd-BCQD/Ti composite electrode exhibited the highest level of electrocatalysis performance. Moreover, Pd and BCQD work in concert to improve the composite electrode's electrochemical performance.
